{{Infobox company | name = ''American Metal Market'' | logo = AMM logo.png | type = [[Subsidiary]] | foundation = 1882 | founder = | location_city = | location_country = | location = | origins = | key_people = | area_served = | industry = [[Mass media|Media]] | products = | services = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | num_employees = | parent = [[Euromoney Institutional Investor]] | divisions = | subsid = | owner = | slogan = | homepage = | dissolved = | footnotes = }} '''''American Metal Market''''' (AMM) is an online provider of industry news and metal pricing information for the U.S. [[steel]], [[nonferrous]] and [[scrap]] markets. Products include a daily publication available in an electronic pdf, live news on the publication's [http://www.amm.com website], a hard-copy magazine and a series of weekly newsletters covering niche markets. The publication also plays host each year to a number of industry conferences and events covering the state of various metal markets. It has been hailed for its impartial coverage of the mining and manufacturing sectors, said to be “as vital to the metal-buyer as the ticker is to [[Wall Street]].” "<ref name="Wilson, A.J. 1979">Wilson, A.J. ''The Pick and The Pen''. London: Mining Journal Books Limited, 1979.</ref>
''American Metal Market'' is a sister publication to London-based [[Metal Bulletin]] and a subsidiary of international publishing group [[Euromoney Institutional Investor]].
==History== First published in 1882 as a weekly news and price paper and never having missed a scheduled publication date, ''American Metal Market'' is considered the longest continuously published newspaper in the industry.<ref name="Wilson, A.J. 1979" /> In April 2002, the daily publication switched from a traditional, hard-copy newspaper to a strictly electronic format, in which form it remains today.
