{{for|the pasta|gnocchi}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}} {{Infobox Minister | name = Pierro Gnudi | image = Piero Gnudi - Tutticittì (cropped).jpg | imagesize = | office = Minister of Tourism and Sport | primeminister = [[Mario Monti]] | predecessor = | successor = | term_start = 16 November 2011 | term_end = 28 April 2013 | office2 = | primeminister2= | predecessor2 = | successor2 = | term_start2 = | term_end2 = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1938|5|17|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Bologna]] | death_date = | death_place = | restingplace = | party = Independent | residence = | alma_mater = [[University of Bologna]] | spouse = | nationality = Italian | religion= | children = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Piero Gnudi''' (born 17 May 1938) is an Italian politician. He served as Italy's minister of tourism and sport in [[Monti Cabinet|the Monti cabinet]] from16 November 2011 to April 2013.
==Early life and education== Piero Gnudi was born on 17 May 1938 in [[Bologna]], Italy.<ref name="unicredit">[http://www.unicreditgroup.eu/en/Governance/Piero_Gnudi.htm Unicredit Board biography]</ref> He graduated from the [[University of Bologna]] with a degree in economics and commerce in 1962.<ref name="business">[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=2692503&ticker=ENEL:IM&previousCapId=93486&previousTitle=ENEL%20SPA BusinessWeek profile]</ref>
==Career== Gnudi is a board member of [[Confindustria]], [[Eni]], Enichem, [[Stet]], Merloni, [[Ferrè]], Beghelli, Irce, and [[Unicredit]].<ref name="grad"/> He sits on the steering committee of Assonime and the executive committee of the [[Aspen Institute]].<ref name="grad"/> He is also the chairman of Profingest, [[Credito Fondiario (Fonspa)]] and vice president of Alma Graduate School.<ref name="grad">[http://www.almaweb.unibo.it/en/almags/eventi/dettaglioEvento.plp?idEvento=48408& Alma Graduate School biography]</ref> He was the board chairman of [[Enel]] from May 2002 to April 2011.<ref name="grad"/> He has also been the president of Rai Holding, Locat, and [[Astaldi]].<ref name="grad"/>
He was appointed minister of tourism and sport on 16 November 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Roe|first=Alex|title=March of the Technocrats: Italy’s Mario Monti’s Ministers|url=http://italychronicles.com/march-technocrats-italys-mario-montis-ministers/|accessdate=8 September 2012|newspaper=Italy Chronicles|date=17 November 2011}}</ref><ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/world-leaders-1/world-leaders-i/italy.html CIA World Leaders]</ref> His term ended on 28 April 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Letta hails strong cabinet with 'record' women presence|url=http://www.ansamed.info/ansamed/en/news/nations/italy/2013/04/27/Letta-hails-strong-cabinet-record-women-presence_8622411.html|accessdate=7 September 2013|newspaper=ANSA|date=27 April 2013}}</ref>
